00:11:41,420 --> 00:11:43,860
 My question that I'm burdened with is,

282
00:11:43,860 --> 00:11:45,640
 does the church have an answer?

283
00:11:45,640 --> 00:11:47,820
 What do we say?

284
00:11:47,820 --> 00:11:52,140
 Does our message have any bearing on a culture in crisis?

285
00:11:52,140 --> 00:11:53,780
 'Cause I can't fix America,

286
00:11:53,780 --> 00:11:55,660
 and we don't need to pontificate about that,

287
00:11:55,660 --> 00:11:58,580
 but I'm very concerned about who is the church

288
00:11:58,580 --> 00:12:00,240
 in the middle of a difficult day.

289
00:12:01,260 --> 00:12:03,740
 And what I love about this passage in Ephesians

290
00:12:03,740 --> 00:12:06,780
 is Paul is gonna show us, hey, there's the problem,

291
00:12:06,780 --> 00:12:09,180
 and here's the depths underneath our problem,

292
00:12:09,180 --> 00:12:10,940
 but then he's gonna lead us to the great physician

293
00:12:10,940 --> 00:12:12,300
 and to see the answer.

294
00:12:12,300 --> 00:12:14,620
 And the answer is not something you do.

295
00:12:14,620 --> 00:12:17,740
 What Paul is gonna show us is what Christ has done.

296
00:12:17,740 --> 00:12:21,500
 As he's watched the enemy rip apart his people,

297
00:12:21,500 --> 00:12:23,220
 Christ comes to act decisively.

298
00:12:23,220 --> 00:12:26,700
 And we're gonna get to see the movement of Christ,

299
00:12:26,700 --> 00:12:29,980
 how he handled the unraveling individually,

300
00:12:29,980 --> 00:12:31,700
 and how he handled it corporately.

301
00:12:31,700 --> 00:12:33,780
 And then we're gonna see how we participate in it.

302
00:12:33,780 --> 00:12:34,940
 Sound good?

303
00:12:34,940 --> 00:12:36,340
 So it's a lot of scripture,

304
00:12:36,340 --> 00:12:38,500
 and we won't necessarily get into the details of all of it,

305
00:12:38,500 --> 00:12:39,820
 but I wanna fly over what he's done.

306
00:12:39,820 --> 00:12:42,660
 And he starts with how he's helped you individually.

307
00:12:42,660 --> 00:12:44,420
 And you see in Ephesians 2, it starts with,

308
00:12:44,420 --> 00:12:46,820
 "And you were dead."

309
00:12:46,820 --> 00:12:50,260
 That Paul looks at our dislocation from God as human beings.

310
00:12:50,260 --> 00:12:53,540
 And he said, "We've been so severed from the author of life

311
00:12:53,540 --> 00:12:55,700
 "that when he tries to find a metaphor for it,

312
00:12:55,700 --> 00:12:57,900
 "he goes to the morgue."

313
00:12:57,900 --> 00:13:00,160
 You are so distant from God,

314
00:13:00,160 --> 00:13:04,040
 the best description of your spiritual state is a graveyard.

315
00:13:04,040 --> 00:13:08,060
 And he says, "And we were dead in our trespasses and sins."

316
00:13:08,060 --> 00:13:09,820
 Trespass means you went someplace

317
00:13:09,820 --> 00:13:11,700
 you were never meant to go.

318
00:13:11,700 --> 00:13:13,180
 And sin means you became something

319
00:13:13,180 --> 00:13:14,260
 you were never meant to be.

320
00:13:14,260 --> 00:13:16,260
 The Bible says all of us have sinned

321
00:13:16,260 --> 00:13:18,820
 and fallen short of the glory of God.

322
00:13:18,820 --> 00:13:20,860
 God made us to be something glorious,

323
00:13:20,860 --> 00:13:23,180
 but there's something wrong with us.

324
00:13:23,180 --> 00:13:26,700
 I'm in spiritual conversations all the time with people,

325
00:13:26,700 --> 00:13:28,060
 and you say, "How?"

326
00:13:28,060 --> 00:13:29,180
 'Cause I'm a pastor.

327
00:13:29,180 --> 00:13:30,340
 People ask, "What do you do for a living?"

328
00:13:30,340 --> 00:13:31,700
 I say, "I'm a pastor,"

329
00:13:31,700 --> 00:13:34,200
 which either destroys the conversation immediately,

330
00:13:34,200 --> 00:13:37,580
 or they start asking questions.

331
00:13:37,580 --> 00:13:39,100
 And you know what's fascinating?

332
00:13:39,100 --> 00:13:39,940
 Is I tell all of them,

333
00:13:39,940 --> 00:13:41,180
 "Though you're beautiful in the image of God,

334
00:13:41,180 --> 00:13:42,340
 "you're desperately broken."

335
00:13:42,340 --> 00:13:44,140
 And no one ever disagrees.

336
00:13:44,140 --> 00:13:45,440
 They're not like, "Well, Ben, I don't know.

337
00:13:45,440 --> 00:13:46,980
 "I mean, let me push back on that."

338
00:13:46,980 --> 00:13:49,240
 I see skies of blue and clouds of white.

339
00:13:49,240 --> 00:13:51,660
 I think to myself, "What a wonderful world."

340
00:13:51,660 --> 00:13:52,500
 No one says that.

341
00:13:52,500 --> 00:13:55,140
 (congregation laughing)

342
00:13:55,140 --> 00:13:56,100
 I say, "We're all broken."

343
00:13:56,100 --> 00:13:56,920
 They're like, "Right?"

344
00:13:56,920 --> 00:13:58,600
 And they start giving me examples.

345
00:13:58,600 --> 00:14:00,040
 And I say, "And you're broken."

346
00:14:00,040 --> 00:14:02,120
 And no one pushes back on that.

347
00:14:02,120 --> 00:14:02,960
 They say, "You're right.

348
00:14:02,960 --> 00:14:04,400
 "I don't even understand what I do.

349
00:14:04,400 --> 00:14:06,520
 "We all know something's wrong with us,

350
00:14:06,520 --> 00:14:08,800
 "but we sometimes misdiagnose the need.

351
00:14:08,800 --> 00:14:10,320
 "Maybe I just need to lose a little weight,

352
00:14:10,320 --> 00:14:11,440
 "maybe gain a little weight,

353
00:14:11,440 --> 00:14:12,720
 "maybe read a self-help book."

354
00:14:12,720 --> 00:14:15,700
 And Paul says, "No, man, if you got an upset tummy,

355
00:14:15,700 --> 00:14:16,660
 "you need Tums.

356
00:14:16,660 --> 00:14:18,480
 "If you got a broken leg, you need surgery.

357
00:14:18,480 --> 00:14:20,520
 "If you're dead, you need a miracle."

358
00:14:20,520 --> 00:14:22,700
 And the problem's deeper.

359
00:14:22,700 --> 00:14:24,540
 The disintegration is further.

360
00:14:24,540 --> 00:14:25,700
 You're not alive.

361
00:14:25,700 --> 00:14:29,200
 In which you walked following the course of the world,

362
00:14:29,200 --> 00:14:32,120
 he said, "There's a social element to our sin.

363
00:14:32,120 --> 00:14:34,340
 "There's a sense of when you get all sinners together,

364
00:14:34,340 --> 00:14:36,480
 "more sin begins to mix into each other

365
00:14:36,480 --> 00:14:39,600
 "and integrate and bump into some very ugly ways."

366
00:14:39,600 --> 00:14:42,880
 Whenever you look historically at genocides,

367
00:14:42,880 --> 00:14:44,420
 people perpetrating enormous evil,

368
00:14:44,420 --> 00:14:47,080
 exterminating millions of people like in Nazi Germany.

369
00:14:47,080 --> 00:14:48,920
 Afterwards, in the interviews of people

370
00:14:48,920 --> 00:14:50,160
 that were just normal people

371
00:14:50,160 --> 00:14:51,940
 who in various ways participated,

372
00:14:51,940 --> 00:14:53,740
 they would ask them, "How could you participate

373
00:14:53,740 --> 00:14:55,520
 "in something you knew was morally wrong?"

374
00:14:55,520 --> 00:14:57,840
 And over and over again, the reports come back,

375
00:14:57,840 --> 00:14:59,520
 because everyone was doing it.

376
00:14:59,520 --> 00:15:03,520
 You've all read about the Ash Conformity Experiment

377
00:15:03,520 --> 00:15:06,640
 where they did tests on college students.

378
00:15:06,640 --> 00:15:08,020
 They would show them pictures,

379
00:15:08,020 --> 00:15:10,080
 which line is the longest, A, B, or C,

380
00:15:10,080 --> 00:15:12,520
 and A was clearly the right answer.

381
00:15:12,520 --> 00:15:15,080
 But the trick on the test was that everyone was in on it

382
00:15:15,080 --> 00:15:16,240
 in the room except one kid,

383
00:15:16,240 --> 00:15:19,080
 and so everyone in the room would clearly pick a shorter one.

384
00:15:19,080 --> 00:15:20,120
 And you'd watch these kids,

385
00:15:20,120 --> 00:15:21,400
 if you've never watched the videos,

386
00:15:21,400 --> 00:15:22,520
 look around like, "What?

387
00:15:22,520 --> 00:15:25,480
 "No, it's A, right guys, right guys, nobody?"

388
00:15:25,480 --> 00:15:28,620
 And over time, as that consistently happened,

389
00:15:28,620 --> 00:15:31,140
 you'd watch them slump in their chair

390
00:15:31,140 --> 00:15:33,660
 and look down, look exhausted,

391
00:15:33,660 --> 00:15:36,500
 until finally 75% of them would give answers

392
00:15:36,500 --> 00:15:37,540
 they knew were wrong.

393
00:15:37,540 --> 00:15:39,260
 Which circle's red?

394
00:15:39,260 --> 00:15:40,220
 Oh, the blue one.

395
00:15:40,220 --> 00:15:47,860
 The push of peer pressure so strong,

396
00:15:47,860 --> 00:15:49,540
 some good self-wisdom you could have

397
00:15:49,540 --> 00:15:50,900
 is knowing how it gets you.

398
00:15:51,900 --> 00:15:53,500
 We followed the Prince of the Power of the Air.

399
00:15:53,500 --> 00:15:55,260
 There's a spiritual element to it.

400
00:15:55,260 --> 00:15:56,740
 I read two books a few years ago,

401
00:15:56,740 --> 00:15:58,260
 people who came to believe in God,

402
00:15:58,260 --> 00:16:00,160
 not because they contemplated the beauty of the world,

403
00:16:00,160 --> 00:16:02,500
 but because they saw the darkness in it.

404
00:16:02,500 --> 00:16:05,100
 And it was more than just biology to them.

405
00:16:05,100 --> 00:16:07,500
 There's something dehumanizing us

406
00:16:07,500 --> 00:16:09,600
 that lets us be so inhumane to each other.

407
00:16:09,600 --> 00:16:12,680
 And then there's a personal element,

408
00:16:12,680 --> 00:16:15,100
 among whom we all lived with the passions of our flesh,

409
00:16:15,100 --> 00:16:17,340
 carrying out the desires of the body, that's the impulse.

410
00:16:17,340 --> 00:16:18,860
 I wanted to see that, so I clicked on it.

411
00:16:18,860 --> 00:16:20,340
 I wanted to touch that, so I did it.

412
00:16:20,340 --> 00:16:23,380
 It's the impulse and the desires of the mind.

413
00:16:23,380 --> 00:16:25,100
 I thought about it.

414
00:16:25,100 --> 00:16:26,820
 I knew that would hurt that person's feelings,

415
00:16:26,820 --> 00:16:28,160
 and I posted it anyway.

416
00:16:28,160 --> 00:16:32,060
 Some of it's impulsive, some of it's deliberate,

417
00:16:32,060 --> 00:16:34,900
 but all of it is death, and we are by nature

418
00:16:34,900 --> 00:16:37,700
 children of wrath like the rest of mankind.

419
00:16:37,700 --> 00:16:41,500
 God is furious when he sees what we've done with the world,

420
00:16:41,500 --> 00:16:42,620
 and I don't blame him.

421
00:16:42,620 --> 00:16:44,580
 And you know, in centuries in the past,

422
00:16:44,580 --> 00:16:46,960
 or centuries years ago, I remember it was kind of awkward

423
00:16:46,960 --> 00:16:48,300
 to talk about wrath.

424
00:16:48,300 --> 00:16:49,920
 I think people get wrath now.

425
00:16:49,920 --> 00:16:52,720
 It's the proper response to injustice.

426
00:16:52,720 --> 00:16:56,780
 Like I remember for me, when I was a little kid,

427
00:16:56,780 --> 00:17:01,220
 going with my father to visit my grandma in the hospital,

428
00:17:01,220 --> 00:17:04,300
 and, or in this nursing home, rather,

429
00:17:04,300 --> 00:17:06,380
 and we showed up and we heard screaming

430
00:17:06,380 --> 00:17:08,660
 when we walked through the door.

431
00:17:08,660 --> 00:17:10,100
 And I remember when we turned the corner,

432
00:17:10,100 --> 00:17:12,500
 we saw the screaming was coming from my grandma.

433
00:17:12,500 --> 00:17:17,220
 They had tied her to a chair in the hallway and left her,

434
00:17:18,180 --> 00:17:21,020
 and she was slumped down and she was screaming, it hurts.

435
00:17:21,020 --> 00:17:24,740
 I'll never forget as a young man, looking at my father,

436
00:17:24,740 --> 00:17:26,540
 who was a gentle man, never yelled,

437
00:17:26,540 --> 00:17:29,620
 but I looked at his face and I saw his arms

438
00:17:29,620 --> 00:17:32,100
 and I saw wrath.

439
00:17:32,100 --> 00:17:36,220
 I saw fury in that man, because you had one job,

440
00:17:36,220 --> 00:17:39,540
 take care of her, and you didn't do it.

441
00:17:39,540 --> 00:17:41,700
 You did the opposite of that.

442
00:17:41,700 --> 00:17:42,660
 And who are you mad at?

443
00:17:42,660 --> 00:17:44,460
 The person who tied her to the chair,

444
00:17:44,460 --> 00:17:47,100
 or all the people who walked down the hall in indifference?

445
00:17:47,100 --> 00:17:48,780
 Both.

446
00:17:48,780 --> 00:17:50,740
 And God looks down at the earth he gave us.

447
00:17:50,740 --> 00:17:53,580
 Can you imagine if you had an estate to hand to people

448
00:17:53,580 --> 00:17:59,100
 and they abused a third of them and misused the funds?

449
00:17:59,100 --> 00:18:00,060
 You'd be furious.

450
00:18:00,060 --> 00:18:01,820
 And God looks at the world and said, man,

451
00:18:01,820 --> 00:18:02,980
 I called you to love each other

452
00:18:02,980 --> 00:18:05,180
 and look what you've done to each other.

453
00:18:05,180 --> 00:18:07,060
 He's furious at it.

454
00:18:07,060 --> 00:18:11,220
 And we're all children of wrath, like the rest of mankind.

455
00:18:11,220 --> 00:18:13,580
 And I know some of us in here say, Ben, I'm not that bad.

456
00:18:13,580 --> 00:18:14,780
 And let me tell you something.

457
00:18:14,780 --> 00:18:17,380
 There's three dead people that Jesus raised

458
00:18:17,380 --> 00:18:18,820
 from the dead in the gospels.

459
00:18:18,820 --> 00:18:22,740
 Jairus' daughter that had died minutes before Jesus arrived.

460
00:18:22,740 --> 00:18:25,180
 The young man who Jesus stopped his funeral,

461
00:18:25,180 --> 00:18:27,060
 literally stopped the funeral beer

462
00:18:27,060 --> 00:18:28,900
 and raised him from the dead.

463
00:18:28,900 --> 00:18:32,500
 And Lazarus, who Jesus waited for days

464
00:18:32,500 --> 00:18:34,300
 before he raised him from the dead.

465
00:18:34,300 --> 00:18:37,380
 All three of them, he raised from the dead.

466
00:18:37,380 --> 00:18:40,300
 The little girl probably looked like she was sleeping,

467
00:18:40,300 --> 00:18:41,220
 probably still warm.

468
00:18:41,220 --> 00:18:43,580
 She had just been dead for minutes.

469
00:18:43,580 --> 00:18:46,060
 Young man had probably been dead a day.

470
00:18:46,060 --> 00:18:47,660
 Body was probably already stiff.

471
00:18:47,660 --> 00:18:51,700
 Lazarus had been in the tomb for days.

472
00:18:51,700 --> 00:18:54,140
 So when Jesus showed up, he said, roll the stone away.

473
00:18:54,140 --> 00:18:57,340
 Mary and Martha went, whoa, whoa, whoa, Jesus, hey,

474
00:18:57,340 --> 00:18:58,340
 he's gonna stink.

475
00:18:58,340 --> 00:19:02,380
 That's the stench of decomposition.

476
00:19:02,380 --> 00:19:06,380
 But here's the interesting thing.

477
00:19:06,380 --> 00:19:07,740
 All three of them, very different.

478
00:19:07,740 --> 00:19:10,340
 Warm, a little stiff, stench.

479
00:19:10,340 --> 00:19:12,740
 But what did they have in common?

480
00:19:12,740 --> 00:19:13,780
 They're all dead.

481
00:19:13,780 --> 00:19:17,780
 It wasn't that he was all dead and she was mostly dead.

482
00:19:17,780 --> 00:19:18,820
 No, they're all dead.

483
00:19:18,820 --> 00:19:22,140
 Just the manifestation of that death looked different.

484
00:19:22,140 --> 00:19:24,340
 So some of us may say, man, I'm not as bad as that guy.

485
00:19:24,340 --> 00:19:25,540
 I don't stink like that person.

486
00:19:25,540 --> 00:19:27,980
 You're right, but you're still dead.

487
00:19:27,980 --> 00:19:30,300
 Like the rest of humanity.

488
00:19:30,300 --> 00:19:32,380
 We're all in a difficult place.

489
00:19:32,380 --> 00:19:36,300
 And unless God does something about it, we can't get out.

490
00:19:36,300 --> 00:19:40,740
 I've told this story a lot in here, but it bears repeating.

491
00:19:40,740 --> 00:19:43,820
 When I was a child, my grandmother had a pool

492
00:19:43,820 --> 00:19:47,900
 in her backyard that years before had been emptied of water,

493
00:19:47,900 --> 00:19:48,980
 emptied of pool water.

494
00:19:48,980 --> 00:19:53,260
 Over the course of years, it had filled with rainwater

495
00:19:53,260 --> 00:19:55,860
 and trees had fallen in it, grass.

496
00:19:55,860 --> 00:19:57,300
 There were snakes in there and frogs.

497
00:19:57,300 --> 00:20:00,580
 And when you're a little kid with a vivid imagination,

498
00:20:00,580 --> 00:20:02,020
 all things evil in the world.

499
00:20:02,020 --> 00:20:05,980
 So if you have a grandma with a pool of evil

500
00:20:05,980 --> 00:20:07,580
 in the backyard, what do you do?

501
00:20:07,580 --> 00:20:10,380
 You play on the edge of it.

502
00:20:10,380 --> 00:20:11,380
 That's what my brother and I would do.

503
00:20:11,380 --> 00:20:12,300
 We'd just go walk in the edge.

504
00:20:12,300 --> 00:20:13,940
 We were like, I can't even stand it.

505
00:20:13,940 --> 00:20:15,380
 All right, walk along.

506
00:20:15,380 --> 00:20:19,100
 Until one day I slipped and I fell in.

507
00:20:19,100 --> 00:20:22,380
 And at that moment, it dawned on me immediately.

508
00:20:22,380 --> 00:20:24,900
 I have to get out of this situation.

509
00:20:24,900 --> 00:20:27,140
 So I waded over to the shallow end.

510
00:20:27,140 --> 00:20:28,900
 I began to run as fast as I could.

511
00:20:28,900 --> 00:20:31,340
 And I went for the leap to try to get myself out.

512
00:20:31,340 --> 00:20:34,740
 I didn't come close.

513
00:20:34,740 --> 00:20:37,500
 I don't know who dug out that pool, but he was motivated.

514
00:20:37,500 --> 00:20:39,820
 I remember I looked up at my brother,

515
00:20:39,820 --> 00:20:40,940
 who's just a year older than me.

516
00:20:40,940 --> 00:20:41,780
 And I'm like, "Ugh."

517
00:20:41,780 --> 00:20:42,620
 And he's like, "Ugh."

518
00:20:42,620 --> 00:20:43,440
 And I'm like, "Ugh!"

519
00:20:43,440 --> 00:20:45,700
 'Cause I realized I can't get out and he can't help me.

520
00:20:45,700 --> 00:20:49,020
 So I did the only thing that was available to me

521
00:20:49,020 --> 00:20:50,580
 at the time, I started crying.

522
00:20:50,580 --> 00:20:55,660
 And I remember as a little five-year-old,

523
00:20:55,660 --> 00:20:58,860
 I'm crying in a pretty terrifying place to me.

524
00:20:58,860 --> 00:21:00,660
 And as I'm doing that, I look through the fence

525
00:21:00,660 --> 00:21:02,780
 and I see a guy that's maybe college age.

526
00:21:02,780 --> 00:21:05,820
 And I see him right as he hears me crying.

527
00:21:07,300 --> 00:21:09,860
 And I watch him drop whatever gardening tool he had.

528
00:21:09,860 --> 00:21:12,060
 And he just started to run.

529
00:21:12,060 --> 00:21:14,700
 And I remember when he got to that fence,

530
00:21:14,700 --> 00:21:16,500
 he just leapt it all in one move.

531
00:21:16,500 --> 00:21:17,900
 It was the coolest thing I'd ever seen.

532
00:21:17,900 --> 00:21:20,340
 And we're all like, "Oh, okay, that was amazing."

533
00:21:20,340 --> 00:21:23,340
 (congregation laughing)

534
00:21:23,340 --> 00:21:27,180
 And he dove into that pool with me and he drew me out.

535
00:21:27,180 --> 00:21:30,420
 It was one of my clearest memories as a child.

536
00:21:30,420 --> 00:21:32,820
 I remember being a little kid, him leaning over

537
00:21:32,820 --> 00:21:36,220
 and looking into my face and saying, "Are you okay, son?"

538
00:21:37,220 --> 00:21:38,540
 And I couldn't answer him.

539
00:21:38,540 --> 00:21:44,420
 I was awestruck by the one who would dive into my chaos

540
00:21:44,420 --> 00:21:46,060
 to set me free.

541
00:21:46,060 --> 00:21:50,540
 And Paul here says, "You were dead,

542
00:21:50,540 --> 00:21:55,860
 but God, being rich in mercy,

543
00:21:55,860 --> 00:21:59,060
 because of the great love with which he loved us."

544
00:21:59,060 --> 00:22:00,020
 Not 'cause of what you did,

545
00:22:00,020 --> 00:22:01,940
 but because of what is housed in him,

546
00:22:01,940 --> 00:22:05,260
 because of that great love, even when you were dead,

547
00:22:05,260 --> 00:22:07,660
 he made you alive with Christ.

548
00:22:07,660 --> 00:22:09,660
 By grace, you've been saved.

549
00:22:09,660 --> 00:22:12,300
 And he raised us with him and seated us with him

550
00:22:12,300 --> 00:22:13,580
 in the heavenly places.

551
00:22:13,580 --> 00:22:18,300
 The Bible is not about making bad people good.

552
00:22:18,300 --> 00:22:20,540
 It's about making dead people alive.

553
00:22:20,540 --> 00:22:25,900
 That Jesus Christ united you in his love.

554
00:22:25,900 --> 00:22:29,460
 He saw the disintegration of our relationship with God

555
00:22:29,460 --> 00:22:32,980
 and Jesus Christ reweaved that relationship.

556
00:22:32,980 --> 00:22:33,820
 How did he do it?

557
00:22:33,820 --> 00:22:36,220
 'Cause there's a vertical beam to this cross.

558
00:22:36,220 --> 00:22:38,460
 He took down the thread of love

559
00:22:38,460 --> 00:22:40,420
 and said, "I'm binding you with me."

560
00:22:40,420 --> 00:22:41,900
 That's what's so great about the language.

561
00:22:41,900 --> 00:22:44,980
 Did you notice three times, "With him, with him, with him."

562
00:22:44,980 --> 00:22:47,460
 You were dead, dead, dead in Adam,

563
00:22:47,460 --> 00:22:50,060
 but you are now raised with me and seated with me,

564
00:22:50,060 --> 00:22:52,540
 alive with me, knit together with Christ.

565
00:22:52,540 --> 00:22:54,580
 You have a future and a hope in him

566
00:22:54,580 --> 00:22:57,220
 because it's by grace, his kindness and compassion,

567
00:22:57,220 --> 00:22:58,580
 you've been rescued.

568
00:22:58,580 --> 00:23:00,700
 Not a result of work so that nobody can boast.

569
00:23:00,700 --> 00:23:02,100
 This is our great message.

570
00:23:02,100 --> 00:23:04,380
 This is the hope of the world

571
00:23:04,380 --> 00:23:06,300
 that we've been rescued by a God

572
00:23:06,300 --> 00:23:08,380
 who has united us with his love.

573
00:23:08,380 --> 00:23:09,780
 Not because of what you've done,

574
00:23:09,780 --> 00:23:11,460
 but because of what he did.

575
00:23:11,460 --> 00:23:12,740
 So that in the ages to come,

576
00:23:12,740 --> 00:23:15,260
 we can be a trophy of his grace,

577
00:23:15,260 --> 00:23:19,060
 the kind of love that could change you from the inside out

578
00:23:19,060 --> 00:23:22,020
 and make you in verse 10, his workmanship.

579
00:23:22,020 --> 00:23:24,780
 Created in Christ Jesus for good works,

580
00:23:24,780 --> 00:23:26,660
 which God has prepared for you beforehand,

581
00:23:26,660 --> 00:23:28,180
 that you would walk in him.

582
00:23:28,180 --> 00:23:30,140
 In an anxious and fractured day,

583
00:23:30,140 --> 00:23:31,780
 he has made you something new.

584
00:23:31,780 --> 00:23:34,100
 There's a dignity and a stability to this.

585
00:23:34,100 --> 00:23:36,500
 It's fascinating.

586
00:23:36,500 --> 00:23:37,900
 Michelangelo's David,

587
00:23:37,900 --> 00:23:41,820
 one of the most famous statues in the world.

588
00:23:41,820 --> 00:23:44,940
 And if you've never gone to see it,

589
00:23:44,940 --> 00:23:46,540
 you'll wait for hours in line

590
00:23:46,540 --> 00:23:49,140
 with people from around the world

591
00:23:49,140 --> 00:23:50,060
 to go into a museum

592
00:23:50,060 --> 00:23:52,140
 that really doesn't have much else except David.

593
00:23:52,140 --> 00:23:54,780
 The whole museum was built for that statue.

594
00:23:54,780 --> 00:23:57,700
 But what most people don't know is

595
00:23:57,700 --> 00:24:01,300
 that statue was initially a discarded stone.

596
00:24:01,300 --> 00:24:05,300
 Many other artists had passed it by.

597
00:24:05,300 --> 00:24:09,220
 And then Michelangelo chose it, carved it,

598
00:24:09,220 --> 00:24:11,940
 and made one of the greatest masterpieces

599
00:24:11,940 --> 00:24:13,060
 humanity's ever produced.

600
00:24:13,060 --> 00:24:14,460
 It's insane if you've never looked at it.

601
00:24:14,460 --> 00:24:16,500
 You expect this marble to move.

602
00:24:16,500 --> 00:24:17,380
 It's a lifelike.

603
00:24:17,380 --> 00:24:21,140
 Now, if stone could think,

604
00:24:21,140 --> 00:24:26,540
 it would be dumb for David to stand up there and think,

605
00:24:26,540 --> 00:24:29,380
 I'm just a discarded stone.

606
00:24:29,580 --> 00:24:31,620
 (congregation laughing)

607
00:24:31,620 --> 00:24:33,620
 So many have passed over me

608
00:24:33,620 --> 00:24:38,820
 because I'm flawed deep inside.

609
00:24:38,820 --> 00:24:44,460
 You'd say, yeah, all that's true.

610
00:24:44,460 --> 00:24:47,540
 But then the master put his hand on you

611
00:24:47,540 --> 00:24:50,140
 and he's made you something else.

612
00:24:50,140 --> 00:24:55,180
 But it'd be equally stupid for David to stand there and say,

613
00:24:55,180 --> 00:24:57,500
 I am David.

614
00:24:58,380 --> 00:24:59,460
 (congregation laughing)

615
00:24:59,460 --> 00:25:00,340
 Drink it in.

616
00:25:00,340 --> 00:25:04,340
 I carved myself out of that stone.

617
00:25:04,340 --> 00:25:05,980
 I chiseled these abs.

618
00:25:05,980 --> 00:25:08,180
 You'd say, whoa, whoa, whoa, whoa.

619
00:25:08,180 --> 00:25:12,980
 Now, you are impressive, but you didn't do that.

620
00:25:12,980 --> 00:25:15,380
 You're something beautiful

621
00:25:15,380 --> 00:25:19,220
 because the master put his hands to you.

622
00:25:19,220 --> 00:25:21,140
 You see the beauty of the gospel?

623
00:25:21,140 --> 00:25:24,460
 It makes us humble and confident at the same time.

624
00:25:24,460 --> 00:25:27,980
 That you can come and say, man, I am something great.

625
00:25:27,980 --> 00:25:29,940
 You're not destined by your flaws.

626
00:25:29,940 --> 00:25:31,460
 They don't have to determine your future.

627
00:25:31,460 --> 00:25:33,100
 You've been made something else.

628
00:25:33,100 --> 00:25:33,940
 Why?

629
00:25:33,940 --> 00:25:36,660
 Because the master knit you together with him.

630
00:25:36,660 --> 00:25:37,980
 You are something else.

631
00:25:37,980 --> 00:25:40,820
 You've been united with him in love.

632
00:25:40,820 --> 00:25:41,660
 You see it?

633
00:25:41,660 --> 00:25:44,220
 And he set out your itinerary

634
00:25:44,220 --> 00:25:47,100
 that we would now step into good works

635
00:25:47,100 --> 00:25:48,380
 that he's prepared for us.

636
00:25:48,380 --> 00:25:52,220
 Now, most people when they preach stop here

637
00:25:52,220 --> 00:25:55,620
 because 10 verses is a lot and that's a good place to stop.

638
00:25:55,620 --> 00:25:58,340
 Paul doesn't and so we don't either.

639
00:25:58,340 --> 00:26:03,700
 Paul goes from what's a really good landing point.

640
00:26:03,700 --> 00:26:06,060
 You're a masterpiece and bring out the band

641
00:26:06,060 --> 00:26:08,220
 and we sing about how a masterpiece I am.

642
00:26:08,220 --> 00:26:11,420
 Paul goes back down and says,

643
00:26:11,420 --> 00:26:13,140
 therefore in light of this,

644
00:26:13,140 --> 00:26:17,740
 remember that at one time you Gentiles in the flesh.

645
00:26:17,740 --> 00:26:18,980
 Gentile is the word ethnos.

646
00:26:18,980 --> 00:26:22,380
 It's the non-Jewish people in the audience.

647
00:26:22,380 --> 00:26:25,100
 He looks at everyone from the nations

648
00:26:25,100 --> 00:26:27,300
 that are diverse ethnically

649
00:26:27,300 --> 00:26:30,780
 and he brings up a source of tension.

650
00:26:30,780 --> 00:26:34,420
 He says, therefore remember that one time you Gentiles

651
00:26:34,420 --> 00:26:36,580
 in the flesh and not just a source of tension

652
00:26:36,580 --> 00:26:39,540
 called the uncircumcision by what is called

653
00:26:39,540 --> 00:26:40,540
 the circumcision.

654
00:26:40,540 --> 00:26:41,500
 Now that's awkward.

655
00:26:41,500 --> 00:26:43,220
 Why does he bring up whether or not you're circumcised?

656
00:26:43,220 --> 00:26:45,260
 That's weird and who would call you that?

657
00:26:45,260 --> 00:26:47,700
 Well, for the Jewish people,

658
00:26:47,700 --> 00:26:50,300
 circumcision was a sign of a covenant with God

659
00:26:50,300 --> 00:26:52,380
 that God has bound himself with us

660
00:26:52,380 --> 00:26:54,460
 and they were meant to be a kingdom of priests

661
00:26:54,460 --> 00:26:56,260
 helping other people know the God

662
00:26:56,260 --> 00:26:58,100
 who had chosen them by his grace.

663
00:26:58,100 --> 00:27:01,500
 But rather than using that graceful position to love others,

664
00:27:01,500 --> 00:27:03,460
 they were using it to lord over others.

665
00:27:03,460 --> 00:27:05,900
 And he says, so they're looking at you

666
00:27:05,900 --> 00:27:07,740
 and calling you the uncircumcision,

667
00:27:07,740 --> 00:27:10,100
 meaning God doesn't like you as much

668
00:27:10,100 --> 00:27:12,180
 because of the nature of your ethnicity.

669
00:27:12,180 --> 00:27:13,900
 It's a racial slur

670
00:27:13,900 --> 00:27:19,660
 and it's got cultural baggage and religious baggage.

671
00:27:19,660 --> 00:27:23,900
 And Paul brings up a really awkward subject.

672
00:27:24,660 --> 00:27:26,740
 This one's great.

673
00:27:26,740 --> 00:27:28,420
 This is getting weird.

674
00:27:28,420 --> 00:27:32,180
 The gospel gets me to heaven,

675
00:27:32,180 --> 00:27:35,020
 but we're ripping each other apart.

676
00:27:35,020 --> 00:27:37,220
 We're not just disintegrated here,

677
00:27:37,220 --> 00:27:38,900
 we're disintegrated here.

678
00:27:38,900 --> 00:27:41,260
 And does the Bible have anything to say

679
00:27:41,260 --> 00:27:43,980
 about how we're culturally ripping each other apart

680
00:27:43,980 --> 00:27:46,660
 because there's all kinds of issues brought up here.

681
00:27:46,660 --> 00:27:50,620
 And Paul keeps pressing on me and keeps making it weird.

682
00:27:50,620 --> 00:27:52,420
 Remember that you were separated from Christ.

683
00:27:52,420 --> 00:27:53,700
 You had no messianic hope,

684
00:27:53,700 --> 00:27:55,620
 alienated from the Commonwealth of Israel.

685
00:27:55,620 --> 00:27:57,300
 There's some national issues here.

686
00:27:57,300 --> 00:27:59,260
 Strangers to the covenant is a promise.

687
00:27:59,260 --> 00:28:01,100
 You didn't even know the words of God.

688
00:28:01,100 --> 00:28:02,580
 And so you had no hope of a future

689
00:28:02,580 --> 00:28:03,700
 without God in the world.

690
00:28:03,700 --> 00:28:05,540
 He's bringing up all these tensions

691
00:28:05,540 --> 00:28:07,420
 that for the Jewish people,

692
00:28:07,420 --> 00:28:09,940
 Gentile was an oppressor, I mean,

693
00:28:09,940 --> 00:28:11,340
 through their whole life,

694
00:28:11,340 --> 00:28:15,340
 back from Pharaoh to Babylon to Persia to Rome.

695
00:28:15,340 --> 00:28:17,260
 So there were religious implications,

696
00:28:17,260 --> 00:28:20,620
 but political implications, social implications,

697
00:28:20,620 --> 00:28:22,740
 religious implications, ethnic ones,

698
00:28:22,740 --> 00:28:23,940
 all kinds of barriers.

699
00:28:23,940 --> 00:28:26,500
 I know it's hard to imagine a time in history

700
00:28:26,500 --> 00:28:28,580
 where people were divided along all these lines.

701
00:28:28,580 --> 00:28:30,340
 Just try to imagine by faith.

702
00:28:30,340 --> 00:28:36,100
 Do we have a message that has anything to say here?

703
00:28:36,100 --> 00:28:40,940
 But now in Christ Jesus,

704
00:28:40,940 --> 00:28:44,380
 you who were once far off have been brought near

705
00:28:44,380 --> 00:28:47,580
 by the blood of Christ.

706
00:28:47,580 --> 00:28:49,180
 For he himself is our peace.

707
00:28:49,180 --> 00:28:50,300
 This isn't internal peace,

708
00:28:50,300 --> 00:28:51,860
 it's talking about us.

709
00:28:51,860 --> 00:28:53,300
 He's our peace, how?

710
00:28:53,300 --> 00:28:55,420
 'Cause he broke down in his flesh

711
00:28:55,420 --> 00:28:57,500
 the dividing wall of hostility

712
00:28:57,500 --> 00:28:59,020
 by abolishing the law of commandments,

713
00:28:59,020 --> 00:29:01,260
 expressing ordinances that he might create in himself

714
00:29:01,260 --> 00:29:03,700
 one new man in place of the two.

715
00:29:03,700 --> 00:29:07,700
 So making peace and might reconcile us both to God

716
00:29:07,700 --> 00:29:09,340
 in one body through the cross

717
00:29:09,340 --> 00:29:11,020
 thereby killing the hostility.

718
00:29:11,020 --> 00:29:13,140
 That's the power of the cross.

719
00:29:13,140 --> 00:29:15,300
 I love the way my friend Derwin Gray says it.

720
00:29:15,300 --> 00:29:17,180
 The cross has a vertical beam

721
00:29:17,180 --> 00:29:19,060
 that I can be reconciled to God.

722
00:29:19,060 --> 00:29:20,860
 And it has a horizontal beam

723
00:29:20,860 --> 00:29:22,620
 that I can be reconciled to you.

724
00:29:22,620 --> 00:29:25,140
 The cross is so powerful.

725
00:29:25,140 --> 00:29:27,020
 It can make dead people alive.

726
00:29:27,020 --> 00:29:28,660
 And the cross is so powerful.

727
00:29:28,660 --> 00:29:31,660
 It can turn former hostility into family.

728
00:29:31,660 --> 00:29:33,220
 That's the power of the cross.

729
00:29:33,220 --> 00:29:35,900
 That we can be united with God in love.

730
00:29:35,900 --> 00:29:38,620
 And we can be united with each other in love.

731
00:29:38,620 --> 00:29:40,860
 The cross of Jesus Christ is sufficient

732
00:29:40,860 --> 00:29:45,620
 to make the dead alive and to make enemies into family.

733
00:29:45,620 --> 00:29:46,700
 It's that powerful.

734
00:29:46,700 --> 00:29:47,660
 How did he do it?

735
00:29:48,660 --> 00:29:52,020
 Through the cross, thereby killing the hostility.

736
00:29:52,020 --> 00:29:55,980
 That in the old Jewish temple, there was a wall.

737
00:29:55,980 --> 00:29:58,020
 Jews could come towards the Holy of Holies

738
00:29:58,020 --> 00:29:59,260
 into the inner sanctum.

739
00:29:59,260 --> 00:30:01,020
 Gentiles could not.

740
00:30:01,020 --> 00:30:03,700
 But he says, Christ didn't just reconcile us to God.

741
00:30:03,700 --> 00:30:06,660
 He broke down that wall, made the two one.

742
00:30:06,660 --> 00:30:09,980
 And now we're reconciled together as one body

743
00:30:09,980 --> 00:30:11,540
 because of his cross.

744
00:30:11,540 --> 00:30:13,840
 There's level ground at the foot of the cross.

745
00:30:13,840 --> 00:30:17,620
 I remember for me, when I first started as a pastor

746
00:30:17,620 --> 00:30:19,660
 right out of college, I was involved in a church

747
00:30:19,660 --> 00:30:22,060
 that did communion where everyone comes down front

748
00:30:22,060 --> 00:30:24,580
 and you'd get break off a piece of the bread

749
00:30:24,580 --> 00:30:27,140
 and you'd dip it in the juice and then eat it.

750
00:30:27,140 --> 00:30:28,220
 I had never been a part of a church.

751
00:30:28,220 --> 00:30:29,700
 I wasn't part of the ones that handed out

752
00:30:29,700 --> 00:30:31,700
 little individual cups of the body of Christ

753
00:30:31,700 --> 00:30:32,540
 and blood of Christ.

754
00:30:32,540 --> 00:30:34,980
 And he would sort of not look at anyone else

755
00:30:34,980 --> 00:30:35,820
 or make eye contact.

756
00:30:35,820 --> 00:30:37,580
 I'm having a moment with my individually wrapped

757
00:30:37,580 --> 00:30:39,300
 body of Christ, blood of Christ.

758
00:30:39,300 --> 00:30:40,180
 Y'all stay over there.

759
00:30:40,180 --> 00:30:41,980
 And so it was the first time it was like this communal thing.

760
00:30:41,980 --> 00:30:43,060
 I thought it was weird at first.

761
00:30:43,060 --> 00:30:43,900
 I wasn't sure.

762
00:30:43,900 --> 00:30:45,380
 And actually, I don't know if we'll ever go back

763
00:30:45,380 --> 00:30:47,340
 to sharing bread again.

764
00:30:47,340 --> 00:30:49,500
 Not up in DC, bleh, spook people.

765
00:30:49,500 --> 00:30:54,020
 But back there, I remember staying up there.

766
00:30:54,020 --> 00:30:56,740
 My job was to hold the bread and say,

767
00:30:56,740 --> 00:30:58,220
 the body of Christ was broken for you.

768
00:30:58,220 --> 00:30:59,500
 The body of Christ was broken for you.

769
00:30:59,500 --> 00:31:00,340
 That was my job.

770
00:31:00,340 --> 00:31:01,380
 And someone else said, the blood of Christ

771
00:31:01,380 --> 00:31:03,020
 was shed for you.

772
00:31:03,020 --> 00:31:06,000
 I remember doing that and I remember this old man

773
00:31:06,000 --> 00:31:06,900
 coming down front.

774
00:31:06,900 --> 00:31:10,460
 This old man had done a lot of impressive things.

775
00:31:10,460 --> 00:31:13,060
 I knew his story, but he still needed this.

776
00:31:13,060 --> 00:31:16,860
 I told him, the body of Christ has been broken for you.

777
00:31:17,780 --> 00:31:20,220
 Then I remember this little girl walked up,

778
00:31:20,220 --> 00:31:21,180
 had to kneel down.

779
00:31:21,180 --> 00:31:24,580
 Like, and the body of Christ was broken for you.

780
00:31:24,580 --> 00:31:28,940
 I watched this sweet old Hispanic grandma come up.

781
00:31:28,940 --> 00:31:32,660
 She said, the body of Christ is broken for you.

782
00:31:32,660 --> 00:31:35,660
 Saw a strong young black man come up.

783
00:31:35,660 --> 00:31:39,140
